<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=98780862447337></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f98780862447337><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=item.html?item=5506&mid=98780862447337>RE: Sucky</a> <a id=fs8 href=item.html?item=5506&mid=98780862447337#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=13763><span id= >DanielSantos</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>93 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Apr 20th 7:17 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.33]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Ok, you guys are right, the 1st guy is a moron. However, I want to make a few points clear.<br><br>If you are a high level melee type, I can't see much use for it (I only have a 27 rogue, but that's high enough to know). DEX has absolutely ZERO effect on how often or hard you hit (at least on a regular hit) as this is determined solely by your ATK (which is your weapon skill, offense skill and STR + any direct ATK buffs like firefist and ).<br><br>However, critical hits, deadly blows and (I understand) also double attacks and duel wielding are effected by dex (not really 100% sure on the double attack and duel wield, but fairly certain). So there is quite a price to pay for a melee person to wear this.<br><br>Also Ahnoksuna, I believe that the formula having to do with calculating movement penalties has somehting to do with your base AGI also, because my base AGI is 70 and that doesn't make me run any slower than somebody with 80. However, if your base AGI is over 75, I think that it actually does have quite a penalty for going under 75. But I kinda think that it's a linar penalty from your base (being 100%) to 1 AGI (being 0% movement) with no bonus for exceeding your base.<br><br>However, formula for AGI being lowered from low health is NOT linar. At level 52, I can be at 15% health and stil have full AGI. I think I start loosing it at around 12% or so, not too sure because I try not to get down that low. At level 4, it seems that you start loosing AGI at about 40%.<br><br>And back to your first "moron", AC is used to determine BOTH whether or not you are hit AND how much damage you take. I have seen nothing in the game to convince me any other than that. So if you have 1 AGI and 800 AC (although that's probably not TOO likely), you will get the same number of time and take the same amount of damage as if you had 255 AGI and 800 AC. ( you just wont be able to run :)<br><br>AGI effects AC, but in odd ways, and this doesn't depend on your base AGI. If you make a character with 70 AGI (i.e., erudite casters, like mine) you will get a huge AC increase if you just get another 5 AGI. At level 52 (with only 145 defense skill), it's about 55 AC difference. I hear that it does this again at 100 and 125, although I really don't know the AC formula that well (but it's determined by defense, AGI and your total AC from armor and spells)<br><br>In closing I would just like to say to RaeinOfTorv that it's better to be thought a fool than to open your mouth and remove all doubt.<br>&nbsp;<br>Yuktii LifeStealer53<br>Necromancer of Quellious<br>Daaniel SilentWhisper - 34 Rogue</td></tr>
